<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-29T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-29T08:00:00-05:00" n="114" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d114">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3703: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva (<persName corresp="#p_GPB1" type="from">Gilbert</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-29T14:00:00+01:00">January 29, 1932—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received January 29—11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>54. I have orally delivered to <persName corresp="#p_CVR1">Cecil</persName> the communication conveyed in your 30, January 28,
                            noon.</p>
                        <pb facs="0199" n="95" xml:id="pg_95"/>
                        <p>He wishes me to express to you his deep personal gratitude for your
                            message. He added, as his personal opinion, that the events at Shanghai
                            had produced a situation which called for immediate and strong action
                            and that if such action were not taken still worse troubles would
                            develop.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_GPB1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>